<subSubSection id="CD57FEC53664D3479E8422B21E02E674" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="DB7237D70FF97922427C2DDCA5A3DF45" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CFACB858B8851B3A3B2E04D16917BA7C" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">
As stated in 
<bibRefCitation id="3ECEF4C23552863B6895B11AD1B252F9" DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.595.7569" author="Chang, L-X" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" pagination="137 - 146" refId="B2" refString="Chang, L-X, Bi, W-X, Ren, G-D, 2016. Two new species of Brachytrycherus Arrow, 1920 from China (Coleoptera, Endomychidae). ZooKeys 595: 137 - 146" title="Two new species of Brachytrycherus Arrow, 1920 from China (Coleoptera, Endomychidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.595.7569" volume="595" year="2016">Chang et al. (2016)</bibRefCitation>
, species of 
<taxonomicName id="C27E6CB4507D30F53AE6239200935564" authority="Arrow, 1920" authorityName="Arrow" authorityYear="1920" class="Insecta" family="Endomychidae" genus="Brachytrycherus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Brachytrycherus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="53622202AA9F2D63B4D6BD6EDAEB4F0B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">Brachytrycherus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resemble those of 
<taxonomicName id="17322581580AE05484C40AFF54E83F04" authority="Chûjô, 1938" authorityName="Chûjô" authorityYear="1938" class="Insecta" family="Endomychidae" genus="Ohtaius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ohtaius" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="4F9D08EE46203E666ECFFC95561FA7B0" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">Ohtaius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken id="532BAC1763BD4B1C09E3A54265E095C0" originalValue="Chûjô">Chujo</normalizedToken>
and 
<taxonomicName id="FEFCD88A22606B096BB05D6EFCB68A18" authority="Tomaszewska, 2005" authorityName="Tomaszewska" authorityYear="2005" class="Insecta" family="Endomychidae" genus="Gerstaeckerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Gerstaeckerus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="28CC0A6F332E58F36E3777671726A302" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">Gerstaeckerus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Tomaszewska in having the body black or blackish brown, elytral maculae transverse, most often orange or yellow. These genera share the feature of having the mandibles chisel-shaped apically. However, 
<taxonomicName id="450C59F3B704DAED7F637598A23EF6AA" authority="Arrow, 1920" authorityName="Arrow" authorityYear="1920" class="Insecta" family="Endomychidae" genus="Brachytrycherus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Brachytrycherus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="97CF51C35C51DA45F9867265A9740955" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">Brachytrycherus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from these genera by the following combination of characters: 1) body less elongate; 2) head with well-developed gular sutures; 3) mesoventral process with sides parallel; 4) maxillary lacinia with tuft of S-like setae apically (
<bibRefCitation id="2A1DE443F1B1A3BAB467ADBBEA33023D" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" refId="B8">Tomaszewska 2005</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A225222528B603B9CF5FADC0EE857BE7" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" type="description">
<paragraph id="DEADB3D9710BDE2B907AEFA4CC61FC30" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">Description</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CC507512978634937E18EB2F41EB6136" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">
(based on 
<bibRefCitation id="7060697FDDC7A6429FD88C0B31F4B5F2" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" refId="B8">Tomaszewska 2005</bibRefCitation>
). Body squat-oval to oval, moderately convex to strongly convex, glabrous or minutely pubescent. Colour dark brown to black, usually with orange or yellow markings on elytra.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9B3089FAB2FA370619CA07580BA0D5A8" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">
Head with gular sutures well developed, widely separated, convergent apically. Antennae (
<figureCitation id="A84607482E2CACBA459FB37E16DE7FD6" captionStart="Figure 20" captionStartId="F20" captionText="Figure 20. Left antenna of Brachytrycherus. A B. conaensis B B. curviantennae C B. femoralis." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.880.34712.figure20" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/346629" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.880.34712.figure20">
Fig. 20
<normalizedToken id="B0BA716C06B3225374C64DB1F4A2585D" originalValue="A–C">A-C</normalizedToken>
</figureCitation>
) 11-segmented, long and slender or rather stout; antennal club 3-segmented, loose. Mandible with chisel-shaped apical tooth and moderately large subapical tooth. Maxilla with terminal palpomere longer than wide, tapering apically; lacinia with tuft of S-shaped apical spines.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B297ADDFE7DC7AF976915AF411C0DB37" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">
Pronotum transverse, widest near 1/2 of pronotal length or apical 1/3; anterior edge with rater large stridulatory membrane; sides weakly undulate or strongly curved. Prosternal process (
<figureCitation id="6D5214A6049B1FD5710DEBE81BD4A435" captionStart="Figure 21" captionStartId="F21" captionText="Figure 21. Prosternal and intercoxal processes of males. A B. conaensis B B. curviantennae C B. femoralis." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.880.34712.figure21" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/346630" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.880.34712.figure21">
Fig. 21
<normalizedToken id="79A02A9B7F212624A785F4D662604077" originalValue="A–C">A-C</normalizedToken>
</figureCitation>
) not extending beyond coxae; narrowly separates procoxae, sides weakly curved outwardly or nearly straight, rounded, weakly truncate or emarginate apically. Mesoventral process (
<figureCitation id="244195E13D1F63FD39B1C850CDB81031" captionStart="Figure 21" captionStartId="F21" captionText="Figure 21. Prosternal and intercoxal processes of males. A B. conaensis B B. curviantennae C B. femoralis." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.880.34712.figure21" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/346630" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.880.34712.figure21">
Fig. 21
<normalizedToken id="75AA28F43F52B427A1B6889C2C615E26" originalValue="A–C">A-C</normalizedToken>
</figureCitation>
) transverse, lateral margins widening apically and overlapping parts of coxae. Elytra anterior edge thickened and raised; sides curved, widest near 1/2 length of elytron; most often with contrasting markings. Tibiae (
<figureCitation id="A8C4BDC7E3FA9741D14C582F5B25109B" captionStart="Figure 22" captionStartId="F22" captionText="Figure 22. Abdomen with ventrite V of males. A B. conaensis B B. curviantennae C B. femoralis." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.880.34712.figure22" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/346631" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.880.34712.figure22">
Fig. 22
<normalizedToken id="14126FC8410B8987B461803AC0FBFB71" originalValue="A–C">A-C</normalizedToken>
</figureCitation>
) most often with sexual characters, in male with different degrees of concavity, curved or tooth.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0DB778B26AC855C7A775FDE31EAD15B6" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">
Abdomen in both sexes with five ventrites. Ventrite V (
<figureCitation id="4209396B1D83E14B025096651AAC3B8A" captionStart="Figure 23" captionStartId="F23" captionText="Figure 23. Left tibia of Brachytrycherus (male). A B. conaensis B B. curviantennae C B. femoralis; 1 protibia; 2 mesotibia; 3 metatibia." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.880.34712.figure23" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/346632" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.880.34712.figure23">
Fig. 23
<normalizedToken id="B20123B47C18F1A60E67B9C6DEE0F220" originalValue="A–C">A-C</normalizedToken>
</figureCitation>
) almost always with sexual characters, posterior margin in male weakly curved or rounded medially, and/or with longitudinal short wrinkles laterally. Male genital segment with paired apophyses fused along nearly 1/3 of its length basally; dorsal plate undivided; additional, internal, V-shaped sclerite present.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5EDA7C9CD07EA9C4BF35F2949FEC01E5" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">
Aedeagus (
<figureCitation id="9AAEA2F03D758EB5AC4AF989B1C8D938" captionStart="Figure 24" captionStartId="F24" captionText="Figure 24. Aedeagus of Brachytrycherus. A B. conaensis B B. curviantennae C B. femoralis; 1 lateral view; 2 apical view. Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.880.34712.figure24" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/346633" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.880.34712.figure24">
Fig. 24
<normalizedToken id="DA5C4F77F366FE2028831D0285979AE2" originalValue="A–C">A-C</normalizedToken>
</figureCitation>
) rather long, heavily sclerotized, without basal curvature. Median lobe branched apically. Tegmen placed basally, ring-shaped, fused with parameres.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="DB2B59F9C8A36FB1FB55FF3BD8A7333A" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="D5D5C2E04C483F76C7250A221797DFC1" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B5C1DC409D17B159F1705BD6F1B56999" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">Oriental Region (India, Laos, Thailand, South of China).</paragraph>
